#open-question(title: [Prospective Baseline Mitochondrial Reserve in At-Risk Populations])[
The core mechanistic prediction of the mtDNA reserve threshold model is that individuals who subsequently develop ME/CFS after a viral trigger will show lower mitochondrial reserve capacity at baseline — before illness — compared to individuals who recover normally. This has never been tested. The gap is not merely methodological: no longitudinal study has enrolled at-risk individuals (e.g. close relatives of ME/CFS patients, individuals with documented EBV primary infection), measured baseline bioenergetics, and followed them prospectively through a viral trigger.

Available tools make this feasible: Seahorse XF analysis of peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMCs) quantifies spare respiratory capacity (SRC) — the difference between maximal and basal oxygen consumption, a direct measure of mitochondrial reserve — in small blood volumes under standard clinical conditions Haplogroup determination adds minimal cost via targeted mtDNA sequencing.

A prospective design would require: (a) enrollment of first-degree relatives of ME/CFS patients and age/sex-matched controls; (b) baseline PBMC bioenergetics (SRC by Seahorse), haplogroup determination, and nuclear mitochondrial gene variants (NDUFAF2, UCP2, FBXL4); (c) follow-up to capture any acute infection episode and post-infection status at 6 and 12 months; (d) ME/CFS diagnosis assessment at 12 months using Canadian Consensus Criteria or ICC.

If lower SRC at baseline predicts ME/CFS conversion after infection, this would constitute the first mechanistic link between inherited mitochondrial characteristics and ME/CFS predisposition. If SRC is equivalent between converters and non-converters, the reserve threshold model would require revision toward nuclear genetic or epigenetic mechanisms. Either outcome would substantially advance the field.

#open-question(title: [R4 -- ET-1 Antagonist Trial for Thermoregulatory Endpoints])[
Bosentan (125 mg BID, dual ET_A/ET_B antagonist) is approved for pulmonary arterial hypertension but has never been trialed for thermoregulatory endpoints in ME/CFS. Cambras et al. demonstrated that skin temperature circadian disruption correlates with ET-1 levels @Cambras2023SkinTemperatureEndothelin, but correlation does not establish causation. A placebo-controlled RCT (n = 40, ET-1 elevated above 2.5 pg/mL) with primary endpoint skin temperature rhythm amplitude and secondary endpoint heat tolerance (environmental chamber) would test whether ET-1 is a causal mediator of thermoregulatory failure. Falsifiable: bosentan reduces skin temperature amplitude variability by more than 30% with no effect in ET-1-normal subgroup. No ME/CFS ET-1 antagonist data.
] <oq:r4-et1-antagonist-trial>

#open-question(title: [R5 -- TRPM3-TRPV1 Crosstalk Validation in Patient-Derived Sensory Neurons])[
TRPM3-TRPV1 functional antagonism is established in rodent sensory neurons but has never been tested in human ME/CFS tissue. Patient-derived iPSC sensory neurons with CRISPR-corrected TRPM3 mutations would directly test whether TRPM3 dysfunction disinhibits TRPV1-mediated heat hyperresponsiveness and CGRP release. Primary endpoints: TRPV1 calcium flux during heat challenge (43°C), CGRP release. Falsifiable: CRISPR correction of TRPM3 normalizes TRPV1 heat response amplitude without requiring TRPV1 antagonist. No ME/CFS patient-derived neuron studies exist.
] <oq:r5-trpm3-trpv1-patient-neurons>

#open-question(title: [R6 -- Waon Therapy Dose-Response Optimization Trial])[
Soejima et al. used 5 sessions/week Waon therapy (60°C, 15 min) over 4 weeks @Soejima2015WaonTherapyCFS, but the minimum effective dose (temperature times duration times frequency) has never been systematically mapped. A four-arm factorial trial (temperature: 55°C vs 60°C vs 65°C; frequency: 2 vs 3 vs 5 sessions/week; duration: 10 vs 15 vs 20 min) with primary endpoint HSP70 protein induction at 4 weeks would identify the optimal trade-off between benefit and tolerability. Falsifiable: 3 sessions/week at 60°C/15 min produces more than 90% of HSP70 induction of the 5x/week protocol. Zero ME/CFS thermal dose-response data.
] <oq:r6-waon-dose-response>

#open-question(title: [R7 -- Spare Respiratory Capacity as Predictive Biomarker for Thermal Therapy])[
Hochecker et al. demonstrated inter-individual variation in WBH-induced mitochondrial improvement (spare capacity increase ranged from near-zero to above 200%) @Hochecker2025HyperthermiaMECFS. Baseline PBMC spare respiratory capacity may predict which patients respond to thermal therapy — analogous to how pre-treatment VO2max predicts cardiac rehabilitation response. Falsifiable: baseline SRC explains more than 50% of variance in thermal therapy response; patients with SRC below 30% of control show negligible benefit. A prospective cohort (n = 50) measuring baseline SRC, administering standardized WBH, and correlating SRC with clinical response is needed.
] <oq:r7-mito-reserve-predictive>

#open-question(title: [R8 -- Gradual Cold Adaptation Safety and Efficacy Trial])[
Cold exposure produces autonomic training benefits in POTS, but ME/CFS cold intolerance and the 45% dropout in the only CFS cryotherapy study suggest poor tolerability. A graded cold adaptation protocol (20°C ambient, decreasing 2°C/week, 30 min/session, 3x/week) with strict orthostatic monitoring would determine whether cold tolerance can be built without triggering PEM in a subset of patients. Falsifiable: gradual cold adaptation over 8 weeks increases cold tolerance by Δ4°C with dropout below 15%; dropout above 30% refutes feasibility. No ME/CFS cold adaptation dose-response data.
] <oq:r8-cold-adaptation-trial>

#open-question(title: [R9 -- HSP70 Kinetic Profiling: Translation, Tissue Distribution, and Therapeutic Window])[
Hochecker et al. measured HSPA5 mRNA (48.33% increase post-WBH) but protein-level kinetics, tissue distribution beyond PBMCs, and the upper safety limit of HSP70 induction remain unknown in ME/CFS. Serial sampling of PBMC HSP70 protein (0, 2, 4, 8, 12, 24, 48, 72 hours post-WBH) plus optional muscle/skin biopsy at peak would define the time course and identify whether excessive HSP70 (above 3x baseline) produces inflammatory cytokine release, establishing the therapeutic window. No ME/CFS HSP70 kinetic data.
] <oq:r9-hsp70-kinetics>

#open-question(title: [R10 -- Heat vs Cold vs Alternating: Optimal Sequencing Trial])[
Heat exposure (WBH/Waon) improves mitochondrial function via HSP70; cold exposure may enhance autonomic flexibility via BAT activation. Whether alternating protocols (heat day 1, cold day 2) produce synergy or whether the thermal stress burden of combining them exceeds the benefit of either alone is unknown. A three-arm trial (heat-only, cold-only, alternating) with endpoints including PBMC respirometry, HRV, cold/heat tolerance, and PEM incidence would determine the optimal sequencing strategy. Falsifiable: alternating protocol outperforms heat-only and cold-only on combined autonomic plus mitochondrial endpoints; cold-only fails without pre-existing mitochondrial reserve.
] <oq:r10-heat-cold-sequencing>

*Immediate feasibility:* Existing infectious mononucleosis cohorts (e.g. those used to identify the 13% ME/CFS conversion rate after EBV) could be retrospectively analyzed for stored baseline biospecimens — if PBMCs were cryopreserved, Seahorse analysis may still be possible. This would provide observational (not prospective) data with shorter timeline.
] <oq:baseline-reserve-prospective>
